Headline::::
Things I’ve learned in time for Mother’s Day




DateTime::::2016-03-06T06:00:26+0000



<p><strong>Bloody hell, I’m going to get a card. </strong>On Valentine’s Day I received a card from our one and a bit year-old daughter, covered in fingerprints. It read: “Thumbody loves you.” Her childminder had obviously gone to a lot of trouble. There were Biro smiley faces and heart-shaped sequins, and despite all that great stuff, I was a bit... thanks? Which is not to say that I don’t love her – the child (the childminder’s a nice lady with a cool bumbag, but we haven’t really got to “love” yet). Not to say that I don’t love the child so much that my life feels like an indie horror film, every 10 minutes another moment of shakily filmed terror, every fear tested until, half-bored, half-wired, a fresh shock alerts you to another nerve. I didn’t know, until I saw her almost slip on a staircase, that my <em>knees</em> could feel love. I didn’t know that when I saw her laugh with my own mother, it would feel like somebody was pressing the “refresh” key in my macerated heart. Cards are for us to give to mothers when we are no longer falling asleep on their necks, or screaming for them at night, for when we are no longer showing them we love them with our entire bodies. I have put it on the fridge though, because that’s what you do.</p>

<p class="pullquote-paragraph">Cards are for us to give to mothers when we are no longer falling asleep on their necks, or screaming for them at night</p>

<p><strong>Everything related to parenting feels impossible.</strong> It starts with sex. Some level of cognitive dissonance is required to lie naked with the intention of having a baby, surely. The maths is wrong. From that to this – I’m not going to argue with “science”, but you know. It’s unlikely. That’s the first impossibility. The second is the birth. I heard myself talking about it recently, merrily chirping away about the hushed argument between doctor and nurse, the blood on the wall. I have a friend who has to get a different bus home from work because they will cry if they pass the hospital. Another who realised she wasn’t sufficiently anaesthetised during a caesarean. There are good stories, too, but far fewer. And this is partly because, of course, birth is something we haven’t quite worked out yet. Not properly. Even during labour I knew there was no way a baby could come out of me. Just because she did does not mean it was possible. It means there are grey areas. Though I’m only virtual seconds into motherhood, the impossibilities multiply. That I would ever sleep longer than two hours. Impossible. That she would ever fit into this cardigan. Nope. That a day will come when she looks after me. We move from one impossibleness to the next, only pausing for a holiday – candles on a cake, the giving of a foot spa. A reminder that another year of impossible things has been survived.</p>

<p><strong>How to say no without guilt.</strong> Since having the baby I’m better at knowing the limits of a day, a relationship, a holiday, a job, myself. It’s not just that I don’t have the time, it’s that I am now aware of how precious that time is, a full hour with only one thing to do. But for the three jobs or nights out I’ll skip, there’ll be one that I will throw everything at. I enter a pub as if walking into my own surprise party, shooting my zingers off liberally, covering the gossip in record time, home before the last tube. No makes it all possible.</p>

<p><strong>Judgment and competition around parenting cannot be extinguished entirely,</strong> merely noted in oneself, like heartburn, and managed. If only there was room to stick this reminder on my fridge between the bloody cards.</p>

<p><strong>When I shared a house in Brighton with four other people, </strong>if someone went upstairs alone we’d say they’d “gone to tidy their room” or: “He needed some me-time,” and it would always be funny, in that way that everything carries innuendo if you are 19 and nobody has died yet. Back then I had no idea I’d ever want time by myself. Myself is boring. But today I crave it like cigarettes. Yet any snatched moments alone are so precious and rare that they often go wasted - I stand in the kitchen, crippled by possibility. Much as I adore my tiny daughter, with a hard and wounding love, the best Mother’s Day gift she could give me is an afternoon without her.</p>

