Anna Jarvis, who invented Mother's Day, hated the commercialisation of the day and said "A printed card means nothing except that you are too lazy to write to the woman who has done more for you than anyone in the world"



Author::::Josella Playton
DateTime::::2016-03-08T14:05:25Z
The countertop microwave oven was introduced in 1967, dishwashers have been around since the 1950s and Mother's Day was invented by Anna Jarvis in the early 20th century, but Mothering Sunday has been around sonce the sixteenth century. Constance Penswick-Smith created the Mothering Sunday Movement in 1914 in the UK, which merged the two days and it has been celebrated in the UK ever since



