Hmm, that's a difficult one - funny, although I was curious about my birth parents, I never felt rejected by them as such, I just accepted that they (well, mainly my natural mother) just wasn't in a position to look after me. Your kids are a bit young for the moment, but I think your only option here is being very open about why they were given up for adoption, even if the details are not necessarily what they want to hear. I was about 18 when I first tried to trace my birth mother - it took a while, but I eventually got some info. Some of it was nice - I learned she'd given me a name, and hesitated a lot before giving me up - some of it less nice, in that I learned my 'father' hit the road the minute he found out about my birth mother's pregnancy. Maybe you could tell them that perhaps one day they can maybe find out the story for themselves and, in the meantime, they have a family, that they are loved and cared for and that's what's important for now? Easy to say, I know, but reassurance like this is important.



